  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3710347300" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3710347300" />
    <a title="Grady" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8034370-grady"><img alt="Grady" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1375016989p2/8034370.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3710347300?book_show_action=true">Dec 22, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Grady" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Grady" href="/user/show/8034370-grady">Grady</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781879960855" href="/book/show/13427917-borderlands-la-frontera">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8034370-grady?shelf=essays">essays</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8034370-grady?shelf=racecraft">racecraft</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3710347300" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15533762646809106334">Sometimes a genuinely creative work - one that synthesizes or works out a new way of understanding the world - can so influence what comes after it that it&apos;s hard to remember how creative it was at the time. I get the sense that Borderlands, written from Gloria Anzaldua&apos;s experience growing up in the borderlands of south Texas, and as an outsider in the world of intellectual writers, represents that kind of creativity. At the time she wrote, anthropology still tended to understand non-Anglo-Amer</span>
  <span id="freeText15533762646809106334" style="display:none">Sometimes a genuinely creative work - one that synthesizes or works out a new way of understanding the world - can so influence what comes after it that it's hard to remember how creative it was at the time. I get the sense that Borderlands, written from Gloria Anzaldua's experience growing up in the borderlands of south Texas, and as an outsider in the world of intellectual writers, represents that kind of creativity. At the time she wrote, anthropology still tended to understand non-Anglo-American cultures from a position of analysis outside of those cultures.<br /><br />Borderlands is cultural analysis with a different frame. Not only does it wrestle with the oppression Anzaldua experienced growing up and as an adult; it also experiments with a practice of resistance to that oppression, crossing typical boundaries of the essay, academic sociology and anthropology, poetry, and spiritual writing - and melding multiple dialects of English and Spanish together - to generate a new, vibrant identity. It doesn't work to call that identity a unity, but part of Anzaldua's purpose is to lift up an underlying coherence at the heart of her experience, and offer her analysis from within that frame. I don't know whether that changed academic anthropology, but it has clearly opened up borderlands studies to such an extent that it's now common to find other writers (of both fiction and nonfiction) positioning themselves within this frame, and easy to forget how new this aspect of Borderlands was at the time. <br /><br />Anzaldua wrote Borderlands before the widespread adoption of 'intersectionality' as a term. I'm sure she must have addressed intersectionality directly in her later writings, and I hope to read them. But it seems to me that Borderlands offers a conceptual alternative to intersectionality: rather than focusing on how everyone's individual experience of society can be understood as a layering of social identities - Latina, female, lesbian - Anzaldua is much more focused on the recognition of a coherent social and cultural identity that grows out of the borderlands experience shared among a group of people. As a lens of analysis, it's not in conflict with intersectionality, but it's not the same. In some ways, it's a better lens for exploring the collision of cultures - in this case, Spanish-Latin American, white Anglo-American, and American Indian. <br /><br />I suspect Anzaldua's approach becomes more complicated as a new borderlands culture gains recognition and organizes itself with multiple social roles and statuses, as all cultures do. Anzaldua movingly critiques gender-based oppression in Mexican culture, and offers an unsourced account of how patriarchy took over Aztec civilization in the 800s. But unless I missed it, she doesn't provide a framework for thinking about how to avoid interpersonal oppression *within* a new culture growing out of the borderlands - she's much more focused on naming and claiming space for it as against its source cultures, although she clearly hopes it will be a vehicle for liberation. <br /><br />Anzaldua's mysticism also permeates Borderlands. On one level, it reflects her own medical and psychological history: she survived frail health and near-death episodes, and by her own report was often at odds with the roles her family envisioned for her. On another, she invokes a shamanic experience of reality - of possession by divine powers - as both a metaphor and a literal ground for her calling to the new identity that she believes grows out of the borderland. In this sense, Anzaldua writes as a prophet, testifying to the objective truth of her vision from the subjective power of her experiences. Because that remains an unusual ground for analysis or arguments among American intellectuals, this aspect of Borderlands still feels very new and unusual. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="15533762646809106334" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

